# Advanced Django ERP & SaaS Development Rules

## Core Stack
- Backend framework: Django
- API framework: Django REST Framework (DRF)
- Database: PostgreSQL
- Frontend: Bootstrap 5 RTL
- Deployment: Docker + Gunicorn + Nginx
- Authentication: JWT or Session Authentication
- Cache: Redis when needed

---

# Architecture Rules

## Project Structure
- Use scalable app-based architecture.
- Separate each business domain into its own Django app.
- Keep business logic outside views.
- Use:
  - services/
  - selectors/
  - utils/
  - repositories/
  structure when appropriate.

Example:
apps/
users/
inventory/
sales/
purchases/
reports/

## Clean Code
- Write production-ready code only.
- Avoid quick fixes and dirty solutions.
- Use reusable components.
- Avoid duplicated logic.
- Follow SOLID principles.

## Naming
- Use clear English naming conventions.
- Variables and functions must be descriptive.
- Database tables should use meaningful names.

---

# Database Rules

## PostgreSQL
- Optimize queries for large-scale ERP systems.
- Always use indexes for:
  - foreign keys
  - barcode fields
  - search fields
  - frequently filtered columns

## ORM Optimization
- Use:
  - select_related()
  - prefetch_related()
  aggressively where needed.

- Avoid N+1 query problems.

## Django ORM & SQL Safety
- Prefer Django ORM (`filter`, `annotate`, `aggregate`, `update`, `bulk_create`, `bulk_update`) for application queries.
- Never embed user or request input in SQL text (`f"...{user_input}"`, `"...".format()`, `%` formatting on SQL strings).
- Raw SQL only when the ORM cannot express the operation (health checks, sequence sync, migrations); always use `%s` placeholders and pass values as the second argument to `cursor.execute()`.
- Table/column identifiers may come from `Model._meta` with `connection.ops.quote_name()` — never from request data.
- Do not use `.raw()`, `.extra()`, or ad-hoc string SQL on `QuerySet`.

## Migrations
- Create safe migrations.
- Never remove production data automatically.
- Use data migrations carefully.

## Audit Logs
- Track:
  - created_by
  - updated_by
  - timestamps
  - deleted status

## Soft Delete
- Prefer soft delete for ERP systems.
- Never permanently delete critical business data.

---

# ERP Business Logic Rules

## Multi Branch Support
- All systems must support:
  - branches
  - warehouses
  - multiple users
  - centralized management

## Permissions
- Implement role-based permissions.
- Support:
  - admin
  - manager
  - employee
  - data entry
  roles.

## Inventory
- Prevent negative stock unless explicitly allowed.
- Track stock movement history.
- Keep barcode support optimized.

## Financial Safety
- Never modify financial records directly.
- Use transaction-safe database operations.

## Data Integrity
- Use atomic transactions for critical operations.

Example:
with transaction.atomic():

---

# SaaS Rules

## Multi Tenant
- Build scalable SaaS-ready architecture.
- Separate tenant data securely.
- Never expose tenant data across accounts.

## Security
- Validate all permissions server-side.
- Prevent privilege escalation.
- Protect APIs with authentication and throttling.
- Use `django-ratelimit` on login, JWT, password change, and health; DRF throttles on API defaults.
- Set `REDIS_URL` in production so rate-limit counters are shared across Gunicorn workers.

## Backups
- Systems must be backup-friendly.
- Design with disaster recovery in mind.

